1. What is Power BI, and what are its three main components?

Definition: Power BI is a business analytics tool by Microsoft that allows you to connect to data, transform it, and create interactive reports and dashboards.

Three components:

Power BI Desktop – Report creation tool (installed on PC).

Power BI Service – Cloud-based service to share, publish, and collaborate on reports.

Power BI Mobile – Mobile app for accessing dashboards anywhere.

2. Name two business use cases for Power BI dashboards.

Sales Performance Tracking – Monitoring revenue, top-selling products, and trends.

HR Analytics – Tracking employee performance, attendance, and turnover.

3. How do you download and install Power BI Desktop?

Go to Microsoft Store or official site: powerbi.microsoft.com/desktop
.

Click Download, run the installer, and follow setup instructions.

4. What is the difference between Power BI Desktop and Power BI Service?

Desktop: Used for creating and designing reports locally.

Service: Used for sharing, collaboration, and cloud-based report distribution.

5. What file extension does a Power BI project use?

.pbix

6. Explain the role of Power Query in Power BI.

Power Query is the ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) tool inside Power BI.

It allows cleaning, reshaping, and combining data before loading it into reports.

7. Why would a business prefer Power BI over Excel for reporting?

Interactive dashboards vs static tables.

Handles larger datasets efficiently.

Easy sharing & collaboration in real-time.

Better data visualizations.

8. Describe one limitation of the free version of Power BI.

You cannot share reports with others unless you have a Pro or Premium license.

9. What is a "published report" in Power BI Service?

A report created in Power BI Desktop and then uploaded (published) to the Power BI Service for viewing, sharing, and collaboration.

10. How does Power BI Mobile enhance accessibility?

Provides real-time access to dashboards and reports on smartphones and tablets.

Supports push notifications for updates.

11. Compare Power BI with Tableau—pros and cons.

Power BI Pros: Lower cost, strong Microsoft ecosystem integration, easy learning curve.

Power BI Cons: Limited advanced customization compared to Tableau.

Tableau Pros: More powerful visualizations, stronger for complex analytics.

Tableau Cons: Expensive, steeper learning curve.

12. Explain how Power BI integrates with Azure services.

Connects with Azure SQL Database, Azure Data Lake, Azure Machine Learning.

Enables AI-driven insights and cloud data storage integration.

13. What are "gateways" in Power BI, and when are they needed?

Gateway connects on-premise databases to Power BI Service.

Needed when data is stored locally (not in the cloud) but must be refreshed in the cloud dashboards.

14. How would you convince a company to adopt Power BI? (ROI argument)

Reduce manual reporting time (saves labor cost).

Real-time data → faster decision-making.

Affordable compared to competitors.

Strong security & Microsoft ecosystem integration.

15. What security features does Power BI offer for sensitive data?

Row-Level Security (RLS) – Restrict data by user.

Data Encryption – Both at rest and in transit.

Microsoft compliance certifications.